by the needs of low-end mobile
users versus desktop users?

00:34:19.672 --> 00:34:21.880
JONAH JONES: So that's a
really interesting question.

00:34:21.880 --> 00:34:26.550
So the vision of the future
of Google Maps that we talked

00:34:26.550 --> 00:34:29.090
about was very, very
platform agnostic.

00:34:29.090 --> 00:34:32.929
It was about this thing
that's personalized to you.

00:34:32.929 --> 00:34:34.969
It's showing the data
that you care about.

00:34:34.969 --> 00:34:37.100
It can dynamically change
for every single place.

00:34:37.100 --> 00:34:40.090
And we wanted to achieve
this on all platforms.

00:34:40.090 --> 00:34:45.780
And what you saw was that I
guess the first hint of that

00:34:45.780 --> 00:34:48.719
was with the new iOS app that
we built with the new design

00:34:48.719 --> 00:34:49.493
language.

00:34:49.493 --> 00:34:51.659
And then a lot of the new
functionality and concepts

00:34:51.659 --> 00:34:53.402
came into the desktop version.

00:34:53.402 --> 00:34:55.360
And now they're starting
to find their way back

00:34:55.360 --> 00:34:56.790
into the mobile version as well.

00:34:56.790 --> 00:34:59.390
So all of the platforms
are kind of-- they're

00:34:59.390 --> 00:35:01.320
almost like in a race.

00:35:01.320 --> 00:35:02.920
Some are readier
earlier than others.

00:35:02.920 --> 00:35:05.540
But we're all heading
toward this unified future.

00:35:05.540 --> 00:35:08.360
And low-end devices are
going to be very much

00:35:08.360 --> 00:35:10.210
an important part
of that as well.

00:35:10.210 --> 00:35:12.720
It's not something that we've
been focusing heavily on

00:35:12.720 --> 00:35:14.270
to begin with, but
definitely we're

00:35:14.270 --> 00:35:17.340
going to be focusing very
much on speed and devices

00:35:17.340 --> 00:35:20.787
with low connectivity and low
CPU and that kind of thing.

00:35:20.787 --> 00:35:22.870
It's really important to
get those things working,

00:35:22.870 --> 00:35:25.025
especially with the
Android 1 phones coming out

00:35:25.025 --> 00:35:25.870
and everything.

00:35:25.870 --> 00:35:27.060
Actually, I haven't
tried one of those yet,

00:35:27.060 --> 00:35:28.851
but I'm really curious
to see how it works.

00:35:31.497 --> 00:35:33.330
AUDIENCE: More generally,
about the process.

00:35:33.330 --> 00:35:35.800
When you do decide
to do a redesign,

00:35:35.800 --> 00:35:37.850
the three lessons are
sort of like three steps.

00:35:37.850 --> 00:35:40.060
Is there a particular order
that you guys followed?

00:35:40.060 --> 00:35:41.768
Did you listen to
users first, or did you

00:35:41.768 --> 00:35:43.011
try to think big on your own?

00:35:43.011 --> 00:35:44.260
Or is it all at the same time?

00:35:44.260 --> 00:35:46.635
JONAH JONES: It's kind of all
at the same time, actually.

00:35:46.635 --> 00:35:50.810
Because the benefit we had
of working on this product

00:35:50.810 --> 00:35:55.350
for seven years, is that we've
run repeated usability studies.

00:35:55.350 --> 00:35:56.860
We're getting
feedback all the time.

00:35:56.860 --> 00:35:59.137
So we know what our
users' pain points are.

00:35:59.137 --> 00:36:00.720
And we know what
areas of the products

00:36:00.720 --> 00:36:03.170
are being underutilized.

00:36:03.170 --> 00:36:05.670
So we knew, for example, that
we had all this great imagery,

00:36:05.670 --> 00:36:07.070
and people weren't finding it.

00:36:07.070 --> 00:36:08.600
So some of them are
explicit issues.

00:36:08.600 --> 00:36:10.690
And other things are
just opportunity areas.

00:36:10.690 --> 00:36:13.425
So we kind of just have
this idea of oh man,

00:36:13.425 --> 00:36:15.640
this could be so much better.

00:36:15.640 --> 00:36:17.070
So that was just
informing things.

00:36:17.070 --> 00:36:19.750
And then obviously, if you
want to change something and do

00:36:19.750 --> 00:36:21.550
something audacious, you've
got to question everything.

00:36:21.550 --> 00:36:22.720
You've got to think big.

00:36:22.720 --> 00:36:24.094
It's all kind of
part and parcel.

00:36:24.094 --> 00:36:26.340
It's not really a step
one, two, three thing.

00:36:26.340 --> 00:36:29.520
ANNETTE LEONG: Similarly,
like when you build a product,

00:36:29.520 --> 00:36:32.460
you want to focus on
a few key use cases.

00:36:32.460 --> 00:36:34.280
And then constantly,
you're looking back

00:36:34.280 --> 00:36:37.330
at what you designed to see
if you are matching those use

00:36:37.330 --> 00:36:38.230
cases.

00:36:38.230 --> 00:36:40.164
And each time you
are not, then you

00:36:40.164 --> 00:36:42.580
go back to the sketching board,
or talk to the researchers

00:36:42.580 --> 00:36:44.700
how we can improve
the products further.

00:36:47.440 --> 00:36:49.240
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:36:49.240 --> 00:36:52.110
I was hoping you could share
a little more about how

00:36:52.110 --> 00:36:54.000
you conduct the user research.

00:36:54.000 --> 00:36:56.370
Both before, during,
and after this process

00:36:56.370 --> 00:36:58.485
for around the world.

00:36:58.485 --> 00:37:01.170
It seems like a pretty
difficult problem.

00:37:01.170 --> 00:37:02.902
I'm wondering what
the main steps were.

00:37:02.902 --> 00:37:04.860
JONAH JONES: I wish we
had a researcher with us

00:37:04.860 --> 00:37:05.651
to talk about this.

00:37:05.651 --> 00:37:09.380
But we basically run a variety
of different research studies.

00:37:09.380 --> 00:37:12.547
We can do super small scale
stuff, even within the company,

00:37:12.547 --> 00:37:14.630
where you just go into a
cafe, and you get someone

00:37:14.630 --> 00:37:15.660
to click on stuff.

00:37:15.660 --> 00:37:19.700
We can bring people in and
have them test things out.

00:37:19.700 --> 00:37:22.280
We can go to people's
homes and see

00:37:22.280 --> 00:37:24.390
how they use things
in the real life.

00:37:24.390 --> 00:37:25.970
There's diary
studies, where you can

00:37:25.970 --> 00:37:28.290
get people to document
the things that they need

00:37:28.290 --> 00:37:29.770
every day, and
what they're using.

00:37:29.770 --> 00:37:32.200
And that can be across
different products.

00:37:32.200 --> 00:37:36.490
Obviously, there's the feedback
that you get from users

00:37:36.490 --> 00:37:40.830
when you get to send feedback
from within the product.

00:37:40.830 --> 00:37:41.997
You can look at the metrics.

00:37:41.997 --> 00:37:44.080
You can see what's getting
clicked and what isn't.

00:37:44.080 --> 00:37:46.260
So we kind of used like a
dozen or so different ways

00:37:46.260 --> 00:37:47.862
of getting this,
because they're all

00:37:47.862 --> 00:37:49.320
flawed in their
own different ways,

00:37:49.320 --> 00:37:50.800
so you're trying
to get around it.

00:37:50.800 --> 00:37:53.340
AUDIENCE: And is it something
that if you look at that data

00:37:53.340 --> 00:37:55.499
and say it's not
really making sense

00:37:55.499 --> 00:37:57.040
for a particular
region of the world.

00:37:57.040 --> 00:38:00.560
You'll go out there and
really attentively study that.

00:38:02.719 --> 00:38:04.260
JONAH JONES: You
can certainly notice

00:38:04.260 --> 00:38:06.890
that there are regional
differences in how people use

00:38:06.890 --> 00:38:08.370
things, the kind of things
that they search for,

00:38:08.370 --> 00:38:09.700
the kind of things
that they need.

00:38:09.700 --> 00:38:11.810
And of course the data is
very different as well.

00:38:11.810 --> 00:38:13.399
The data in the
Bay Area is great.

00:38:13.399 --> 00:38:15.940
You go somewhere else, maybe
the data is a lot lower quality.

00:38:15.940 --> 00:38:17.940
So things vary a lot.

00:38:17.940 --> 00:38:19.119
It's really interesting.

00:38:19.119 --> 00:38:21.410
ANNETTE LEONG: And sometimes
when you design a feature,

00:38:21.410 --> 00:38:25.110
you may need multiple rounds of
research and usability testing

00:38:25.110 --> 00:38:25.990
for that.

00:38:25.990 --> 00:38:29.470
And then we had a long period
of time with internal dogfood,

00:38:29.470 --> 00:38:33.160
where we collected a lot of
feedback from internal users.

00:38:33.160 --> 00:38:35.170
So we actually
during that round we

00:38:35.170 --> 00:38:37.800
made the feedback
button super prominent.

00:38:37.800 --> 00:38:40.700
And people wherever they use
and run into any problem,

00:38:40.700 --> 00:38:42.880
they can just click
there and that

00:38:42.880 --> 00:38:46.422
would allow them to easily
file a request or bug.

00:38:46.422 --> 00:38:48.130
JONAH JONES: It's also
worth pointing out

00:38:48.130 --> 00:38:50.010
that we're a very diverse team.

00:38:50.010 --> 00:38:53.210
Like you can hear that neither
of us are American here.

00:38:53.210 --> 00:38:55.030
We have teams all
over the world.

00:38:55.030 --> 00:38:56.900
And so I think
that actually helps

00:38:56.900 --> 00:38:58.620
in bringing a very
global perspective

00:38:58.620 --> 00:39:00.210
in building a product like this.

00:39:00.210 --> 00:39:02.470
That we're not all just
focused on one place.

00:39:02.470 --> 00:39:04.428
We've got people from
different point of views.

00:39:04.428 --> 00:39:05.070
That helps too.

00:39:05.070 --> 00:39:06.820
AUDIENCE: That was my
additional question.

00:39:06.820 --> 00:39:07.870
Sorry for interrupting.

00:39:07.870 --> 00:39:11.110
But I wanted to know how
localized the maps are.

00:39:11.110 --> 00:39:14.500
And how different they are
in Asian countries, or let's

00:39:14.500 --> 00:39:16.670
say in the Middle East.

00:39:16.670 --> 00:39:18.390
JONAH JONES: So
we try and achieve

00:39:18.390 --> 00:39:21.950
a balance between localization
where it makes sense,

00:39:21.950 --> 00:39:24.980
because we want people
to feel familiar.

00:39:24.980 --> 00:39:27.970
But we also want Google Maps
to be a consistent experience,

00:39:27.970 --> 00:39:30.190
so that you recognize
it as you travel around.

00:39:30.190 --> 00:39:33.000
So you'll see some
elements of the design,

00:39:33.000 --> 00:39:37.010
like we have localized public
transit icons, for example.

00:39:37.010 --> 00:39:41.824
But the things like-- what else
was a good example-- things

00:39:41.824 --> 00:39:43.240
like restaurant
icons or something

00:39:43.240 --> 00:39:44.990
like that are kind of
the same everywhere.

00:39:44.990 --> 00:39:48.164
So we try and achieve a
balance of localization

00:39:48.164 --> 00:39:49.705
where it makes sense
to be different.

00:39:49.705 --> 00:39:52.440
But otherwise we try and
have a consistent style

00:39:52.440 --> 00:39:55.947
so that everyone can predict
how to use the product.

00:39:55.947 --> 00:39:57.530
ANNETTE LEONG: And
in terms of the UI,

00:39:57.530 --> 00:40:01.260
we also created
the framework that

00:40:01.260 --> 00:40:02.690
supports multiple languages.

00:40:02.690 --> 00:40:06.840
Like some language like you
have to read from right to left.

00:40:06.840 --> 00:40:09.810
So we had to make sure
that the framework could

00:40:09.810 --> 00:40:12.761
allow a format like that.

00:40:12.761 --> 00:40:14.760
AUDIENCE: I was wondering
if you could talk more

00:40:14.760 --> 00:40:17.801
about the differences between
the mobile app versus the web

00:40:17.801 --> 00:40:19.800
UI, which you were
showcasing more in this talk.

00:40:19.800 --> 00:40:23.204
In particular, I run a UX
design agency in our office.

00:40:23.204 --> 00:40:24.870
We were talking about
how much we really

00:40:24.870 --> 00:40:27.125
enjoy the updates
in the web app.

00:40:27.125 --> 00:40:29.080
And in the mobile
UI, we kept getting

00:40:29.080 --> 00:40:33.691
lost in how you even start
a navigation session.

00:40:33.691 --> 00:40:35.690
And it looked like
something's transferred well,

00:40:35.690 --> 00:40:36.460
and other things didn't.

00:40:36.460 --> 00:40:37.650
And maybe somethings
you're working on.

00:40:37.650 --> 00:40:40.430
So I was just wondering if you
could shed more light on that.

00:40:40.430 --> 00:40:42.370
JONAH JONES: I would
characterize that

00:40:42.370 --> 00:40:46.150
as saying that we have
this vision of the future.

00:40:46.150 --> 00:40:48.060
And then the mobile and
the desktop versions

00:40:48.060 --> 00:40:49.830
were being developed
concurrently.

00:40:49.830 --> 00:40:52.610
And so they're almost
like slightly different

00:40:52.610 --> 00:40:54.940
interpretations of
that same future.

00:40:54.940 --> 00:40:58.099
So the teams are sitting
right next to each other.

00:40:58.099 --> 00:40:59.765
So the desktop team
were borrowing ideas

00:40:59.765 --> 00:41:01.860
from the mobile
team and vice versa.

00:41:01.860 --> 00:41:04.010
So it's mostly the same.

00:41:04.010 --> 00:41:06.260
There are some things that
are deliberately different.

00:41:06.260 --> 00:41:08.060
There are a few things that
are kind of unintentionally

00:41:08.060 --> 00:41:09.380
different, that we want to fix.

00:41:09.380 --> 00:41:10.530
But I think gradually
you're going

00:41:10.530 --> 00:41:12.363
to see these things
converging increasingly.

00:41:12.363 --> 00:41:15.910
And especially with the
new material design staff.

00:41:15.910 --> 00:41:19.070
We really want to have
an experience where

00:41:19.070 --> 00:41:22.720
it's very, very consistent as
you go from desktop to tablet

00:41:22.720 --> 00:41:25.290
to mobile to watch
to Glass, whatever.

00:41:29.190 --> 00:41:32.789
AUDIENCE: So for new features
like highlighting roads

00:41:32.789 --> 00:41:34.330
next to points of
interest, are there

00:41:34.330 --> 00:41:36.730
any plans to make those
accessible via the API

00:41:36.730 --> 00:41:39.499
or any of the new features that
you guys talked about today?

00:41:39.499 --> 00:41:41.290
JONAH JONES: That's a
really good question.

